{"title_page": "Lykan HyperSport", "text_new": "{{short description|Limited production mid-engine sports car manufactured by Middle Eastern automobile manufacturer W Motors}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Lykan HyperSport\n| image = Lykan HyperSport.jpg\n| caption = The Lykan HyperSport in Monaco\n| manufacturer = [[W Motors]]\n| aka = \n| designer = [[Ralph Debbas]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.formtrends.com/inside-w-motors/|title=Inside W Motors, Creators of the Lykan Hypersport|last=Gallina|first=Eric|last2=|date=2013-11-15|website=Form Trends|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref><br>Anthony Jannarelly<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1101528_lykan-hypersport-designer-starts-own-car-company|title= Lykan HyperSport designer|date= 22 December 2015|author=Viknesh Vijayenthiran|publisher= Motor Authority|accessdate= 13 February 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180213135247/https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1101528_lykan-hypersport-designer-starts-own-car-company|archive-date= 13 February 2018|url-status= live}}</ref><br>Benoit Fraylon<ref name=\":1\" />\n| production = 2013\u20132016\n| model_years = 2013\u20132016\n| assembly = [[Dubai]], United Arab Emirates\n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])<!-- per [[WP:CARCLASS]], this should not be changed to \"supercar or hypercar\" -->\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| engine = 3.7 L [[twin-turbocharged]] [[Flat-six engine|flat-six]]\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Sequential manual transmission|sequential manual]]<br>7-speed [[Dual-clutch transmission|dual-clutch]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2625|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4480|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1944|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1170|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1380|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| sp = uk\n| predecessor = \n| successor = [[Fenyr SuperSport]]\n| doors = 2\n}}\nThe '''Lykan Hypersport''' is a [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] limited production [[supercar]] manufactured by [[W Motors]], a [[United Arab Emirates]] based company, founded in 2012 in [[Lebanon]] with the collaboration of Lebanese<ref>{{Cite web|title = W Motors: A Conversation With The Designer Of The World's Most Controversial Supercar|url = http://www.complex.com/sports/2014/06/w-motors-interview-dubai|website = Complex|accessdate = 29 November 2015|author = Branden J. Peters|date = 16 June 2014|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208120640/http://www.complex.com/sports/2014/06/w-motors-interview-dubai|archive-date = 8 December 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> and Italian engineers.<ref>{{Cite web|title = CEO and Founder of W Motors on the Lykan Hypersport {{!}} Haute Dubai Magazine (Dubai, UAE)|url = http://www.hautedubaimagazine.com/motoring/wmotorslykanhypersportinterview/|website = www.hautedubaimagazine.com|accessdate = 29 November 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208074428/http://www.hautedubaimagazine.com/motoring/wmotorslykanhypersportinterview/|archive-date = 8 December 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> It is the first [[sports car]] to be designed and produced indigenously in the [[Middle East]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/06/30/autos/w-motors-first-arab-supercar/|title=W Motors: The world's first Arab supercar manufacturer|date=30 June 2015|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=13 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914011101/http://edition.cnn.com/2015/06/30/autos/w-motors-first-arab-supercar/|archive-date=14 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe production of the car was limited to a total of just seven units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/w-motors-lykan-hypersport/26119|title=W Motors unveils US$3.4 million Lykan Hypersport|website=www.gizmag.com|access-date=7 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226103936/http://www.gizmag.com/w-motors-lykan-hypersport/26119/|archive-date=26 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The first pre-production Lykan HyperSport was unveiled to the public at the [[Qatar Motor Show]] in February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lykan HyperSport|url=http://www.wmotors.ae/pressreviews_images/1384265200English%20Press%20Release%20-%20W%20Motors%20Lykan%20HyperSport-%20Dubai%20Motor%20Show.pdf|work=W Motors|date=November 2013|accessdate=18 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226100126/http://www.wmotors.ae/pressreviews_images/1384265200English%20Press%20Release%20-%20W%20Motors%20Lykan%20HyperSport-%20Dubai%20Motor%20Show.pdf|archivedate=26 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Pricing and sales==\nAt {{USD}}3.4 million, the Lykan HyperSport was the third most expensive production car at time of its production. The HyperSport is the first car to have headlights with embedded jewels; they contain titanium LED blades with 440 diamonds (15cts);<ref>{{cite web|title=Lykan Hypersport|url=http://www.wmotors.ae/#3|publisher=wmotors|accessdate=15 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126191122/http://www.wmotors.ae/#3|archive-date=26 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> although buyers had a selection of rubies, diamonds, yellow diamonds, and sapphires to be integrated into the vehicle's [[headlight]]s at purchase based on the colour choice. The car also uses a holographic display system on the centre console with interactive motion features, as well as [[gold]] stitching on the seats. In June 2015, the Abu Dhabi Police purchased a Lykan HyperSport.<ref>{{cite web|website=news.com.au|url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/innovation/motoring/abu-dhabi-police-adds-one-of-worlds-rarest-cars-lykan-hypersport-to-garage/news-story/258522315abf1ab80813183df962f3dc|title=Abu Dhabi police adds one of world\u2019s rarest cars, Lykan HyperSport, to garage|access-date=28 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220161914/http://www.news.com.au/technology/innovation/motoring/abu-dhabi-police-adds-one-of-worlds-rarest-cars-lykan-hypersport-to-garage/news-story/258522315abf1ab80813183df962f3dc|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The Abu Dhabi Police car is included in the total of seven, meaning only six were available for purchase by customers. W Motors has since confirmed all cars were sold.\n\n== Specifications ==\n\n=== Powertrain ===\nThe Lykan HyperSport is powered by a 3.7 litre (3,746 cc) twin-turbocharged [[flat-six engine]] developed by [[Ruf Automobile]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmotors.ae/hypersport-specs.html|title=Lykan Hypersport Specifications|date=3 February 2013|website=W Motors|accessdate=5 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021122006/http://www.wmotors.ae/hypersport-specs.html|archive-date=21 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> producing a  (claimed) maximum power output of {{convert|581.6|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} at 7,100 rpm and {{convert|960|Nm|lb.ft|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 4,000 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmotors.ae/models/lykan_hypersport|title=Specification sheet|work=W Motors|accessdate=21 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230093701/http://www.wmotors.ae/models/lykan_hypersport|archive-date=30 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The engine has a mid-rear mounted position and transfers power to the rear wheels. There have been no independent tests of the power output of the vehicle.\n\n=== Transmission ===\nThe Lykan HyperSport was available with either a 6-speed [[Sequential manual transmission|sequential manual]] or a 7-speed [[Dual-clutch transmission#Porsche (VW GROUP)|dual-clutch PDK]] transmission. The transmission is paired with a limited-slip differential and is mounted transversely at the rear of the car.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmotors.ae/pdf/lykan_supersport_specifications.pdf|title=Lykan HyperSport Technical Data|website=W Motors|access-date=1 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130204410/https://www.wmotors.ae/pdf/lykan_supersport_specifications.pdf|archive-date=30 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspension ===\nThe Lykan HyperSport uses a [[MacPherson strut|MacPherson strut suspension]] on the front axle, and [[multi-link suspension]] with horizontal coil over shock absorbers at the rear axle. [[Anti-roll bar|Anti-roll bars]] are also installed at both axles.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Wheels ===\nThe Lykan HyperSport is equipped with forged aluminum wheels with diameters of 19 inches at the front and 20 inches at the rear. The tyres are Pirelli P Zeros with codes of 255/35 ZR 19 for the front and 335/30 ZR 20 for the rear. The brakes have ventilated ceramic composite discs, with a diameter of 380 mm each and using six-piston aluminium callipers at the front and rear.<ref name=\":0\" />\n==Performance==\nThe manufacturer claims a top speed of {{convert|395|km/h|mph|abbr=on|0}}, depending on the gear ratio setup. The car has claimed acceleration times of 2.8 seconds for 0-100 km/h (0-62 mph) and 9.4 seconds for 0-200 km/h (0-125 mph), though no independent tests have been conducted. There was a demonstration of the car by W Motors in 2013 in Dubai, in which they claim to have recorded the car's performance.\n\n==Film version==\nA Lykan HyperSport was featured in the film [[Furious 7|''Furious 7'']]. The film's car coordinator Dennis McCarthy explained in an interview<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2015/3/24/8282803/furious-7-car-coordinator-interview A Q&A with Dennis McCarthy, the man behind Furious 7's insane cast of cars]</ref> that the Lykan HyperSports used in the film were not production models but purpose-build by W Motors for the film using the same molds, but cheaper material (fiberglass instead of carbon fiber) and a simpler chassis. Of the ten produced in the film, one was returned to W Motors and is displayed in their showroom. The other nine were destroyed.\n\nA single Lykan HyperSport replica was also used in the 2018 British ''Fast & Furious Live'' show. It has since been sold to a private owner.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:2016-03-01 Geneva Motor Show 0992.JPG|Lykan HyperSport at the [[Geneva Motor Show#2016|2016 Geneva Motor Show]].\nFile:Principaute de Monaco april 2014 2014-04-22 00-52.jpg|Rear view.\nFile:Lykan HyperSport (17674415112).jpg|Lykan Hypersport at [[Auto Shanghai]] 2015\nFile:Lykan Hypersport - Abu-Dhabi Police Edition.jpeg|Lykan Hypersport - Abu-Dhabi Police Edition on display at GITEX 2015\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n{{Sister project links\n |1= |collapsible= |display=Lykan HyperSport |position= |style=\n |wikt=no |c=Category:Lykan HyperSport |commonscat=Category:Lykan HyperSport |n=no |q=no |s=no |author=no |b=no |v=no\n |voy=no |d=Q13408086 |m=no |mw=no |species=no |species_author=no\n}}\n{{Official website|https://wmotors.ae/lykan-hypersport.html}}\n\n{{Automotive industry in Lebanon}}\n{{Automotive industry in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2013]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by boxer engines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Limited production mid-engine sports car manufactured by Middle Eastern automobile manufacturer W Motors}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Lykan HyperSport\n| image = Lykan HyperSport.jpg\n| caption = The Lykan HyperSport in Monaco\n| manufacturer = [[W Motors]]\n| aka = \n| designer = [[Ralph Debbas]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.formtrends.com/inside-w-motors/|title=Inside W Motors, Creators of the Lykan Hypersport|last=Gallina|first=Eric|last2=|date=2013-11-15|website=Form Trends|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref><br>Anthony Jannarelly<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1101528_lykan-hypersport-designer-starts-own-car-company|title= Lykan HyperSport designer|date= 22 December 2015|author=Viknesh Vijayenthiran|publisher= Motor Authority|accessdate= 13 February 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180213135247/https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1101528_lykan-hypersport-designer-starts-own-car-company|archive-date= 13 February 2018|url-status= live}}</ref><br>Benoit Fraylon<ref name=\":1\" />\n| production = 2013\u20132016\n| model_years = 2013\u20132016\n| assembly = [[Dubai]], United Arab Emirates\n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])<!-- per [[WP:CARCLASS]], this should not be changed to \"supercar or hypercar\" -->\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| engine = 3.7 L [[twin-turbocharged]] [[Flat-six engine|flat-six]]\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Sequential manual transmission|sequential manual]]<br>7-speed [[Dual-clutch transmission|dual-clutch]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2625|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4480|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1944|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1170|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1380|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| sp = uk\n| predecessor = \n| successor = [[Fenyr SuperSport]]\n| doors = 2\n}}\nThe '''Lykan Hypersport''' is a [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] limited production [[supercar]] manufactured by [[W Motors]], a [[United Arab Emirates]] based company, founded in 2012 in [[Lebanon]] with the collaboration of Lebanese<ref>{{Cite web|title = W Motors: A Conversation With The Designer Of The World's Most Controversial Supercar|url = http://www.complex.com/sports/2014/06/w-motors-interview-dubai|website = Complex|accessdate = 29 November 2015|author = Branden J. Peters|date = 16 June 2014|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208120640/http://www.complex.com/sports/2014/06/w-motors-interview-dubai|archive-date = 8 December 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> and Italian engineers.<ref>{{Cite web|title = CEO and Founder of W Motors on the Lykan Hypersport {{!}} Haute Dubai Magazine (Dubai, UAE)|url = http://www.hautedubaimagazine.com/motoring/wmotorslykanhypersportinterview/|website = www.hautedubaimagazine.com|accessdate = 29 November 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208074428/http://www.hautedubaimagazine.com/motoring/wmotorslykanhypersportinterview/|archive-date = 8 December 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> It is the first [[sports car]] to be designed and produced indigenously in the [[Middle East]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/06/30/autos/w-motors-first-arab-supercar/|title=W Motors: The world's first Arab supercar manufacturer|date=30 June 2015|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=13 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914011101/http://edition.cnn.com/2015/06/30/autos/w-motors-first-arab-supercar/|archive-date=14 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe production of the car was limited to a total of just seven units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/w-motors-lykan-hypersport/26119|title=W Motors unveils US$3.4 million Lykan Hypersport|website=www.gizmag.com|access-date=7 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226103936/http://www.gizmag.com/w-motors-lykan-hypersport/26119/|archive-date=26 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The first pre-production Lykan HyperSport was unveiled to the public at the [[Qatar Motor Show]] in February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lykan HyperSport|url=http://www.wmotors.ae/pressreviews_images/1384265200English%20Press%20Release%20-%20W%20Motors%20Lykan%20HyperSport-%20Dubai%20Motor%20Show.pdf|work=W Motors|date=November 2013|accessdate=18 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226100126/http://www.wmotors.ae/pressreviews_images/1384265200English%20Press%20Release%20-%20W%20Motors%20Lykan%20HyperSport-%20Dubai%20Motor%20Show.pdf|archivedate=26 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Pricing and sales==\nAt {{USD}}3.4 million, the Lykan HyperSport was the third most expensive production car at time of its production. The HyperSport is the first car to have headlights with embedded jewels; they contain titanium LED blades with 440 diamonds (15cts);<ref>{{cite web|title=Lykan Hypersport|url=http://www.wmotors.ae/#3|publisher=wmotors|accessdate=15 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131126191122/http://www.wmotors.ae/#3|archive-date=26 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> although buyers had a selection of rubies, diamonds, yellow diamonds, and sapphires to be integrated into the vehicle's [[headlight]]s at purchase based on the colour choice. The car also uses a holographic display system on the centre console with interactive motion features, as well as [[gold]] stitching on the seats. In June 2015, the Abu Dhabi Police purchased a Lykan HyperSport.<ref>{{cite web|website=news.com.au|url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/innovation/motoring/abu-dhabi-police-adds-one-of-worlds-rarest-cars-lykan-hypersport-to-garage/news-story/258522315abf1ab80813183df962f3dc|title=Abu Dhabi police adds one of world\u2019s rarest cars, Lykan HyperSport, to garage|access-date=28 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220161914/http://www.news.com.au/technology/innovation/motoring/abu-dhabi-police-adds-one-of-worlds-rarest-cars-lykan-hypersport-to-garage/news-story/258522315abf1ab80813183df962f3dc|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The Abu Dhabi Police car is included in the total of seven, meaning only six were available for purchase by customers. W Motors has since confirmed all cars were sold.\n\n== Specifications ==\n\n=== Powertrain ===\nThe Lykan HyperSport is powered by a 3.7 litre (3,746 cc) twin-turbocharged [[flat-six engine]] developed by [[Ruf Automobile]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmotors.ae/hypersport-specs.html|title=Lykan Hypersport Specifications|date=3 February 2013|website=W Motors|accessdate=5 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021122006/http://www.wmotors.ae/hypersport-specs.html|archive-date=21 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> producing a  (claimed) maximum power output of {{convert|581.6|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} at 7,100 rpm and {{convert|960|Nm|lb.ft|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 4,000 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmotors.ae/models/lykan_hypersport|title=Specification sheet|work=W Motors|accessdate=21 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230093701/http://www.wmotors.ae/models/lykan_hypersport|archive-date=30 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The engine has a mid-rear mounted position and transfers power to the rear wheels. There have been no independent tests of the power output of the vehicle.\n\n=== Transmission ===\nThe Lykan HyperSport was available with either a 6-speed [[Sequential manual transmission|sequential manual]] or a 7-speed [[Dual-clutch transmission#Porsche (VW GROUP)|dual-clutch PDK]] transmission. The transmission is paired with a limited-slip differential and is mounted transversely at the rear of the car.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmotors.ae/pdf/lykan_supersport_specifications.pdf|title=Lykan HyperSport Technical Data|website=W Motors|access-date=1 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130204410/https://www.wmotors.ae/pdf/lykan_supersport_specifications.pdf|archive-date=30 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspension ===\nThe Lykan HyperSport uses a [[MacPherson strut|MacPherson strut suspension]] on the front axle, and [[multi-link suspension]] with horizontal coil over shock absorbers at the rear axle. [[Anti-roll bar|Anti-roll bars]] are also installed at both axles.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Wheels ===\nThe Lykan HyperSport is equipped with forged aluminum wheels with diameters of 19 inches at the front and 20 inches at the rear. The tyres are Pirelli P Zeros with codes of 255/35 ZR 19 for the front and 335/30 ZR 20 for the rear. The brakes have ventilated ceramic composite discs, with a diameter of 380 mm each and using six-piston aluminium callipers at the front and rear.<ref name=\":0\" />\n==Performance==\nThe manufacturer claims a top speed of {{convert|395|km/h|mph|abbr=on|0}}, depending on the gear ratio setup. The car has claimed acceleration times of 2.8 seconds for 0-100 km/h (0-62 mph) and 9.4 seconds for 0-200 km/h (0-125 mph), though no independent tests have been conducted. There was a demonstration of the car by W Motors in 2013 in Dubai, in which they claim to have recorded the car's performance.\n\n==Film version==\nA Lykan HyperSport was featured in the film [[Furious 7|''Furious 7'']]. The film's car coordinator Dennis McCarthy explained in an interview<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2015/3/24/8282803/furious-7-car-coordinator-interview A Q&A with Dennis McCarthy, the man behind Furious 7's insane cast of cars]</ref> that the Lykan HyperSports used in that movie were not production models but purpose-build by W Motors for the movie. They were built using the same molds, but cheaper material (fiberglass instead of carbon fiber) and a simpler chassis. Of the 10 produced in the movie, one was returned to W Motors and is displayed in their showroom. The other nine were destroyed.\n\nA single Lykan HyperSport replica was also used in the 2018 British ''Fast & Furious Live'' show. It has since been sold to a private owner.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:2016-03-01 Geneva Motor Show 0992.JPG|Lykan HyperSport at the [[Geneva Motor Show#2016|2016 Geneva Motor Show]].\nFile:Principaute de Monaco april 2014 2014-04-22 00-52.jpg|Rear view.\nFile:Lykan HyperSport (17674415112).jpg|Lykan Hypersport at [[Auto Shanghai]] 2015\nFile:Lykan Hypersport - Abu-Dhabi Police Edition.jpeg|Lykan Hypersport - Abu-Dhabi Police Edition on display at GITEX 2015\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n{{Sister project links\n |1= |collapsible= |display=Lykan HyperSport |position= |style=\n |wikt=no |c=Category:Lykan HyperSport |commonscat=Category:Lykan HyperSport |n=no |q=no |s=no |author=no |b=no |v=no\n |voy=no |d=Q13408086 |m=no |mw=no |species=no |species_author=no\n}}\n{{Official website|https://wmotors.ae/lykan-hypersport.html}}\n\n{{Automotive industry in Lebanon}}\n{{Automotive industry in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2013]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by boxer engines]]\n", "name_user": "Damien Linnane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilm version:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lykan_HyperSport"}
{"title_page": "Henri Richard", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian ice hockey player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{redirect|Pocket Rocket|the miniature motorcycle|Minibike|the snooker player with this nickname|Graeme Dott|the sailboat class|Laminex Pocket Rocket}}\n{{Distinguish|Henri Richards}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = Chex Henri Richard.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption = \n| played_for = [[Montreal Canadiens]]\n| league = [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Centre]]\n| shoots = Right\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 7\n| weight_lb = 160\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1936|2|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|3|06|1936|2|29}}\n| death_place=[[Laval, Quebec]], Canada\n| career_start = 1955\n| career_end = 1975\n| halloffame = 1979\n}}\n'''Joseph Henri Richard''' (February 29, 1936 \u2013 March 6, 2020) was a Canadian professional [[ice hockey]] player who played [[Centre (ice hockey)|centre]] with the [[Montreal Canadiens]] in the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) from [[1955\u201356 NHL season|1955]] to [[1974\u201375 NHL season|1975]]. His brother, Canadiens' legend and fellow [[Hockey Hall of Fame]]r [[Maurice Richard]], was nicknamed \"The Rocket\". Fifteen years younger and three inches shorter, Henri went by  \"'''The Pocket Rocket'''\". Henri won 11 [[Stanley Cup]]s as a player, the most in NHL history. In 2017 Richard was named one of the '[[100 Greatest NHL Players]]' in history.<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Greatest NHL Players|url=https://www.nhl.com/fans/nhl-centennial/100-greatest-nhl-players|website=NHL.com|accessdate=January 1, 2017|date=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHenri Richard was born on February 29, 1936 in Montreal, the son of Alice (Laram\u00e9e) and On\u00e9sime Richard.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=Ozsu-y42zbcC&pg=PT23&dq=alice+Laram%C3%A9e+richard&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjZ94zltoroAhWAlnIEHdzPC5QQ6AEwAHoECAYQAQ]</ref> His father worked as a machinist for the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]], specifically at the [[CPR Angus Shops|Angus Yards]].  His older brother [[Maurice Richard]] played hockey for the [[Montreal Canadiens]] beginning in 1942, when Henri was six years old.  Maurice Richard quickly became a superstar player for the Canadiens, earning the nickname Rocket Richard, and Henri Richard wished to emulate his brother and go into hockey.  Henri joined the junior Montreal Canadiens as a 15 year old, and led the [[Quebec Major Junior Hockey League|QMJHL]] in scoring for two consecutive seasons before being promoted to the NHL.<ref name=\"NYT obit\">{{cite web |last1=Goldstein |first1=Richard |title=Henri Richard, Hall of Fame Center for Montreal Canadiens, Dies at 84 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/06/sports/hockey/henri-richard-dead.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Globe obit\">{{cite web |last1=Hawthorn |first1=Tom |title=Montreal Canadiens great Henri Richard won a record 11 Cups |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/article-montreal-canadiens-great-henri-richard-won-a-record-11-cups/ |website=theglobeandmail.com |publisher=The Globe and Mail |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gazette obit\">{{cite web |title=Habs icon Henri Richard was a fierce competitor who won record 11 Cups |url=https://montrealgazette.com/sports/hockey/nhl/hockey-inside-out/habs-icon-henri-richard-a-fierce-competitor-who-won-record-11-cups |website=montrealgazette.com |publisher=Postmedia |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC obit\">{{cite web |last1=Lindeman |first1=Tracey |title=Canadiens legend Henri Richard dies at 84 |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/nhl-montreal-canadiens-henri-richard-obit-1.5488245 |website=cbc.ca |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n[[File:Henri Richard.jpg|thumb|right|Henri Richard signing autographs in 2011]]\n\nHenri Richard began his professional career playing on the same team as his older, more famous brother; and comparisons between himself and his brother were easy to make.  He was nicknamed \"Pocket Rocket\" while still a junior in reference to his brother's nickname \"Rocket Richard,\" as well as the fact that Henri Richard was shorter than his brother.<ref name=\"NYT obit\" /><ref name=\"Gazette obit\" />\n\nThe two Richard brothers' style of play was quite different.  Maurice Richard was famous for driving at the net with brute force; however Henri Richard preferred tactical playmaking and outthinking the opponent.  Maurice shot left; Henri shot right.  Maurice was a goalscorer who was the first to score [[50 goals in 50 games]], and led the league in goals on five occasions; Henri led the league in assists twice, in [[1957\u201358 NHL season|1957\u201358]] and in [[1962\u201363 NHL season|1962\u201363]].  Maurice was strong; Henri was fast.  However, they had one thing in common: both were willing to be physical on the ice.  <ref name=\"Gazette obit\" /><ref name=\"Macleans\">{{cite web |last1=Frayne |first1=Trent |title=How the \u201cPocket Rocket\u201d beat his kid-brother jinx |url=https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1958/3/29/how-the-pocket-rocket-beat-his-kid-brother-jinx |website=macleans.ca |publisher=Maclean's |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=March 29, 1958}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Montreal Canadiens coach [[Toe Blake]] kept the two Richard brothers apart on the ice, fearing that his star Maurice Richard would give up goalscoring opportunities to his younger brother.  However, one game against Chicago a couple of injuries forced Blake to play the Richard brothers together, and Henri assisted Maurice on a goal in the third period, and from then on he played the brothers together on a line with hall-of-famer [[Dickie Moore (ice hockey)|Dickie Moore]].  Initially, Maurice would watch out for his brother, and go after anyone who pushed his younger brother around; but after Henri won a fight while Maurice was stuck in the penalty box, Maurice realized that his brother could take care of himself, and stopped looking out for him.  Toe Blake later said that playing with Henri forced Maurice to become a better player, and helped prolong Maurice's career.  Later in 1958, when Maurice Richard was injured, Toe Blake moved [[Marcel Bonin]] to the line to take Maurice's place, and Henri Richard's line continued to produce goals, showing the world that Maurice Richard was not simply carrying his little brother. <ref name=\"Globe obit\" /><ref name=\"Macleans\" />\n\nIn 1957\u201358, he was named to the [[NHL All-Star Team|First All-Star Team]] and in [[1958\u201359 NHL season|1959]] he was named to the Second All-Star Team; he was also named to the Second All-Star Team in [[1960-61 NHL season|1961]] and [[1962-63 NHL season|1963]]. <ref name=\"Globe obit\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe scored the Stanley Cup clinching goal at the 2:20 mark of the first overtime of Game Six in the [[1966 Stanley Cup Finals]] against the [[Detroit Red Wings]], when a pass bounced off of Henri Richard's body into the net while Detroit's goalie [[Roger Crozier]] was still sprawled out on the ice.  In the [[1971 Stanley Cup Finals]], Richard scored the game-tying and Stanley Cup-winning goals in Game Seven against the [[Chicago Black Hawks]].  This particular final was a controversial one for Henri Richard, when he was benched in Game 5 after accusing coach [[Al MacNeil]] of discriminating against French-speaking players on the team in an interview, an accusation that resulted in MacNeil getting death threats and requiring a bodyguard for himself and his family during Game 7.  Henri Richard went on to call MacNeil \"the worst coach I have ever played for.\"  Despite winning the Stanley Cup, MacNeil was demoted to coaching the Canadiens' junior hockey team, the Nova Scotia Voyageurs; while after captain [[Jean Beliveau]] retired, Henri Richard was promoted to team [[Captain (ice hockey)|captain]].  MacNeil and Richard later reconciled. <ref name=\"NYT obit\" /><ref name=\"Globe obit\" /><ref name=\"Gazette obit\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=1966 NHL Stanley Cup Playoffs Summary |url=https://www.hockey-reference.com/playoffs/NHL_1966.html |website=hockey-reference.com |publisher=Sports Reference, Inc. |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Montreal Canadiens: Stanley Cup Champions 1971 |url=http://bigmouthsports.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/1971-Stanley-Cup-Playoff-boxscores-MTL.pdf |website=bigmouthsports.com |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Zadarnowski |first1=Andrew |title=Coaching The Farm: 1968-1981 \u2014 Al MacNeil presided over the greatest era |url=https://www.habseyesontheprize.com/history/2018/4/20/17250550/coaching-the-farm-montreal-canadiens-1968-1981-al-macneil-presided-over-the-greatest-era |website=Eyes on the Prize |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=April 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NHL obit\">{{cite web |title=Henri Richard dies at 84, won NHL-record 11 Cup titles with Canadiens |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/henri-richard-dies/c-315927688 |website=NHL.com |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement and legacy==\n\n[[File:HHOF July 2010 Canadiens locker 08 (H. Richard).JPG|thumb|right]]\n\nHenri Richard served as captain of the Canadiens in 1971 until his retirement in 1975, after his team was eliminated in the playoffs by the [[Buffalo Sabres]].  He was the ninth player to reach 1,000 career points, with 358 goals and 688 assists in 1,256 games. His 1,256 regular-season games played in a Canadiens uniform are a franchise record.  Henri won 11 [[Stanley Cup]]s as a player, the most in NHL history.  Only one other athlete in North American professional sports has achieved winning eleven championships in his respective league\u2014[[Bill Russell]] of the [[National Basketball Association|NBA's]] [[Boston Celtics]].  Henri also scored two Stanley Cup winning goals, one of only five players to have done so.<ref name=\"NYT obit\" /><ref name=\"Globe obit\" /><ref name=\"Gazette obit\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/henri-richard-dies/c-315927688|title=Henri Richard dies at 84, won NHL-record 11 Cup titles with Canadiens|last=|first=|date=March 6, 2020|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NHL obit\" />\n\nHe always wore the number 16, which was retired on December 10, 1975 by the Canadiens in his honour; he insisted that the proceeds from his jersey retirement night be donated towards the construction of a gymnasium for an orphanage.<ref name=\"Gazette obit\" />  He was elected to the [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] in 1979.<ref name=\"NYT obit\" />  In 1998, he was ranked number 29 on ''[[The Hockey News]]''' [[list of the 100 Greatest Hockey Players]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kay |first1=Jason |title=THE TOP 100 NHL PLAYERS OF ALL-TIME, THROWBACK STYLE |url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/the-top-100-nhl-players-of-all-time-throwback-style |website=thehockeynews.com |publisher=The Hockey News |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=April 2, 2015}}</ref>  He would later serve as an ambassador for the Canadiens' organization.<ref name=\"NHL obit\" /> In 2015, it was announced that Richard had been diagnosed with [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.journaldemontreal.com/2015/08/29/une-pensee-pour-henri-richard|title=Une pens\u00e9e pour Henri Richard|last=Durocher|first=Pierre|website=Le Journal de Montr\u00e9al|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> He died on March 6, 2020 at the age of 84, in [[Laval, Quebec]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6640221/henri-richard-death/|title=Henri Richard, legendary Montreal Canadiens hockey star, dead at 84|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[regular season|Regular&nbsp;season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n| 1951\u201352\n| Montreal Nationale\n| QJHL\n| 49\n| 23\n| 32\n| 55\n| 35\n| 4\n| 1\n| 0\n| 1\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| 1952\u201353\n| Montreal Nationale\n| QJHL\n| 46\n| 27\n| 36\n| 63\n| 55\n| 7\n| 4\n| 5\n| 9\n| 4\n|-\n| 1952\u201353\n| [[Royal Montreal Hockey Club|Montreal Royals]]\n| [[QSHL]]\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| 1953\u201354\n| [[Montreal Jr. Canadiens]]\n| QJHL\n| 54\n| 56\n| 53\n| 109\n| 85\n| 7\n| 6\n| 7\n| 13\n| 6\n|-\n| 1954\u201355\n| Montreal Jr. Canadiens\n| QJHL\n| 44\n| 33\n| 33\n| 66\n| 65\n| 4\n| 3\n| 1\n| 4\n| 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[1955\u201356 NHL season|1955\u201356]]\n| [[Montreal Canadiens]]\n| [[NHL]]\n| 64\n| 19\n| 21\n| 40\n| 46\n| 10\n| 4\n| 4\n| 8\n| 21\n|-\n| [[1956\u201357 NHL season|1956\u201357]]\n| Montreal Canadiens\n| NHL\n| 63\n| 18\n| 36\n| 54\n| 71\n| 10\n| 2\n| 6\n| 8\n| 10\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[1957\u201358 NHL season|1957\u201358]]\n| Montreal Canadiens\n| NHL\n| 67\n| 28\n| 52\n| 80\n| 56\n| 10\n| 1\n| 7\n| 8\n| 11\n|-\n| [[1958\u201359 NHL season|1958\u201359]]\n| Montreal Canadiens\n| NHL\n| 63\n| 21\n| 30\n| 51\n| 33\n| 11\n| 3\n| 8\n| 11\n| 13\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\" \n| [[1959\u201360 NHL season|1959\u201360]]\n| Montreal Canadiens\n| NHL\n| 